  <app loc="1"><rdg source="#PET1878">Petrie (1878, 22, Plate XV): CRONMAOL or CRONMAEL</rdg>
   <note></note>
  </app>
 </listApp>          
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>of Cruindmáel?</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary"> 
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>The reading followed here is by <ref source="#HIG1987">Higgins (1987)</ref>, which differs from Petrie's reading and drawing, which do not agree with each other. The text would appear to simply contain a personal name, presumably Cruindmáel (a compound of <ref target="https://dil.ie/13226"><hi rend="italic">cruind</hi></ref> 'round, circular' and <ref target="https://dil.ie/31242"><hi rend="italic">máel</hi></ref> 'crop-headed, shorn, tonsured'). The expected Old Irish genitive of this name would be Cruindmaíl. CRONMAOIL could be a later (Middle Irish) spelling of this form.</p></item>                      
                       </list>
            </div>
